A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican attorneys have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Unlike what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing the federal elections in the United States.
And in line with that, most American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made it harder for people to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states in 2011.
The new election laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to proof of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the vote and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities therefore rushed to extend the practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required ID card costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are thus disproportionately affecting young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more to it.
In many states students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Moreover, those same States authorise members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Spanish vote.
It seems that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the vote in eight states.
They also limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have led to a decline in the registration rate of new electors in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented no more than 13% of the state's voters.
The same thing happened with the Hispanics.
These represent no more than 11% of the electorate, which equates to 24% of citizens voting in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have been fiercely opposed to the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage was partly limited.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed legislation requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, there is no denying that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say for sure whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this respect, the measures will undermine partly the American democratic system.
