The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a great stir last summer, and rightly so.
In fact, this boson is believed to be part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it's about the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But physicists aren't entirely sure that it's Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, let's assume it's Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim.
There is, in this great world, a general and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that it also has a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other side are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories' website The Particle Adventure, which is, by the way, extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I might point out here, are not the exotic creatures we might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon, or "light particle", that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment - much like throwing a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that it's another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it, you have to reach extremely high energies, kind of like a frozen pond where only a thick rock can slide through the surface.
This is why a huge particle accelerator like CERN's (the big hadron collider is a 27 km ring!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
An analogy to the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a refrigerator door by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way) don't.
What can all these investigations "contribute" to?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of MS.
Many, on the other hand, are eager to meet, for the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that will fill certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, such as that it does not propose any explanation for gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (other ups!).
But we haven't found such differences at CERN yet.
The impact
The impact of such research on our daily lives is difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong to say that it will not have any.
So you see, in the early '60s, the pioneers of laser in the laboratories had no idea what revolution their work would bring.
They were interviewing the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, the laser was initially considered a "laboratory device".
Just imagine that.
And applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light sensor in 1969 during his research on optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this camera now serves as an eye for all digital devices in the world, earning him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That doesn't mean, of course, that LHC activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
