It is a file-slicing phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter, unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "tossing" the whole.
The objective is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by up to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed with each increase in computing power.
The life of the net has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoin deposits have been stolen.
