A Constitution with Force in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as far as the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two months to finish its work.
And for almost two years now, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial turmoil.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "betray his word" and "trample on the right".
The Commission's supporters say it is a step to speed up the institutional and political crisis and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short time period that forces the Brothers to abandon their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is wreaking havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote my text or I maintain full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday on the text.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As was expected, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are also pleased that one of the few discrepancies in the day was expressed at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent Assembly clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on late yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all scrutiny, remains ultimately identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it merely a publicity ploy.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could arise in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule on all this".
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms regarding the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those under the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
As the military wishes, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
The prosecution of civilians in military courts will also not be prohibited, as advocated by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy continues and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
She said the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to be on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The head of state's supporters demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the belly of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
AIF identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptism pillar" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and the overflowing nets.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
The faithful walk here on the Via Crucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin for "Sorrowful Way").
It begins at the Fortress of Antonio, the Pretorio, where the trial was held, and continues through the streets of the Old City, going to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of the Anointing and the place of burial of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian World Emblem, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the site where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 CE.
As is traditional, people of different religions leave notes with their wishes, which will then come true.
Making a vertical trip
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge from the enemies, which Herod the Great had built in the year 25 BC for his family.
They are found on mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, only those who are dedicated to climbing can.
The rest of you can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
There are bus services from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly inhabited on the top of the mountain.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all on one trip.
But it's worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting ones.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It contains the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the Judean desert caves, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It's worth a visit to the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
In his painting exhibition he has canvases of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bath museum, which is a few rooms of old Turkish bathrooms with model figures of visitors and bathers from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are strictly prohibited.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And they're calling the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries where they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
Israel's three main tourist areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinarium and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air warms to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they bathe there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: 417 meters below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily holds even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to take courses of salt water, brine and curative mud and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to get their broken nerves in order.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street with your "same" symbol, luck will be in your favor.
In Jaffa you can find newlyweds who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to take pictures.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "taking" the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to be carried in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily converted to shekel (currently 1-3$,8 shekel).
Urban transportation is mainly made up of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
It's actually from an underground funicular.
Traveling by any type of public transport costs 6 shekel and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed on Saturdays.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops are closed and public transportation is suspended.
But Sunday morning begins a new work week.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels only serve kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that combine milk and meat.
There is a wide selection of beef and lamb dishes, coconut milk-prepared soups and desserts, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, falafel, which are grilled chicken balls, fruits and vegetables.
You don't see stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the contrary, many well-fed cats "walk about" in a spectacular way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Rumors are a favorite of crowded places and they don't turn down candy.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) a day.
Besides the insurance, which goes out for $15 a day.
And the rent of a bicycle will cost you 15 shekel a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekel.
Israel by figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to visit and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, a figure that is 51% higher than the same figure in 2010, before the visa regime was cancelled on 9 February 2011.
