"For now, fooling the brain isn't that easy".
The theme of augmented reality, so popular among modern technology enthusiasts, is seen normally in recent times mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At its annual conference in early summer, Google demonstrated a moving model and later in November it was revealed that Microsoft had also submitted an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, it was clear that for the company's scientists, the glasses were already a past stage.
They are attracted to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of your research group's study?
- We're dedicated to person-computer interaction, but we're also trying to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its great mass has been caught in the work stage with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and no Xbox is sold without Kinect today, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Even though Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information input has improved (the system receives more data), and output is still not very good.
We're trying to change this, we're working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
We must free the world of computing from our own, the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, it is pending to resolve the privacy issue, since you do not always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not loose movements, but shorter ones.
Furthermore, gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a wristband that recorded the movement of the bones and muscles.
It's very large for now, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- What's that like?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can of soda?
You'll speak and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do right now?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work primarily on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine a person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, since they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Are you lacking resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with 3D recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the question is not about megapixels, but about the quality of the array and the depth.
From this last point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on Z.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond lab, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
I would be very useful for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact to make frames per second more.
- And you don't need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second the reflected signal receiver.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible slide.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the camera's location curvature and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smartphone in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to a smartphone,
