- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the film "Iron Man", but to any simple mortal.
There is a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile response!
Hands can't feel a thing!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth well could be the addition of touch sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is using the second hand as a support for the image.
He records the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really geared toward bringing tangibleness to these "air images", for example, interference from several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a similar feeling to what you would feel if someone were blowing you in the fingertips, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, which is also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool your brain?
Make him think he feels what he seems to feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here's another challenge we're going to have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space think they're going to an open space, almost endless.
Right now, fooling the brain isn't that easy, it's still a lot of work to do for years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, who find many things in a state of total conception.
