Šimon Ornest: We want to build positive energy in our concerts
They say the world is coming to an end in just under a month. What do you think?
It's just one of many other alarming news stories we like to grab.
The Tap Tap music group likes to joke about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to prevent it.
And in December, you're hosting a really original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain this to our readers?
This is a state charity event we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential that the end of the Mayan calendar has for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December at 9 p.m., we will organise 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at about the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
It was my idea at first, then we went to forge the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
To celebrate the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, T-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The group The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is titled "End of the world, canceled".
It's currently very popular on YouTube, can you hear it at charity concerts?
Of course it will, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
All the performers will sing it at the same time at all three concerts.
The hymns will be linked together simultaneously thanks to the live special broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the lead role of Jesus in the music video, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We also work together with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, besides organising many charity events and concerts...
We are committed to participating in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the money raised from the end-of-the-world concerts be used for?
To equip the Studeo Barrierless Education Centre, which we have completed for the sixth consecutive year with the civil partnership Tap in Jedličkův Ustáv.
Students at Jedličkův Ustav school regularly receive visiting teachers with whom they have fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have the financial means to pay teachers and we are making an effort to make this possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to create a program that is appealing to all generations, including children.
