Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of European Space Agency ministers last week, Poland was accepted as the 12th ESA member.It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and for the following years took part in the Agency's project commission.
However, Poland's journey into the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw, where on 6 December 1933 he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the moon's hidden face was named after him.
Already in 1925 a dredge was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who the author of the proposal was and the outbursts of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dredge or to brake it.
Information about this dressing is limited to the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is clear that the investigation has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - powietrzna torpeda i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the outbreak of war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine first referred to the society with four very extensive articles devoted to astronomy.
In one of them, by Professor M. Subotowicze, it was proposed to create a society devoted to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was obvious that cosmic research was a future-oriented discipline.
From early 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of actual scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a maximum range of 14.5 km and its mission was to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aero Institute, whose first aerial tests were started in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research of space on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
