The number marks the person and this number is six hundred and sixty-six".
If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive prospects: throwing the Shah overboard was not allowed, as if he did, he would jeopardize the confidence of his allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later intensified with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the US, their fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck is themed on an episode of this story, which garnered a small hit for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the Canadian Embassy residence.
The CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, which was helped by a bizarre cover story: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew that was examining the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of sexes
The plan outlined by exfiltration expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production company even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example might be the series Ocean's Eleven).
The film combines moods, and on one side we find well-documented footage of Tehran, and the credits show iconic photographs of the time of the events, which were captured in the same way in the film, and there's not much difference in that.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the office hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respected director and his acting style has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Little Goodbye, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which the action doesn't take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is "winding" in Canada.
The film's best scenes take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of true events, and the opening sequence of the embassy shoot is impressive for its synoptic ability, which at the same time conveys the emotion of the confusion and the unpredictability that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn't offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he does quite well. Sometimes he adds something to the reality: here everything doesn't come out so elegantly (the scene of the crisis at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the rampant search for his trail become crazy).
Argo's weakness is the uncontrollability that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserve more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses some dramatic trace, but it is a film that can be continued with moderate interest, appreciation of its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that's going to be hard.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, that is enough.
