The MVRDV architecture study shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "mountain of books"- 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company near the library, points out, "Besides, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder what we need a library for these days.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom town located at the gates of Rotterdam that barely deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having stood up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, it was decided a few years ago to contribute in some way to the general culture and to copy the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how policymakers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: we had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master of the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun as well as cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and attended the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged its shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called `Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is raised in its intended location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and town hall buildings.
In early November the book mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the 'Dutch National Wood Award 2012'.
Thus, the little town without history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy centre, now boasts a contemporary architectural work.
But most of all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it's a book paradise under a cheese.
True, there is an elevator that transports us right into the center of this mountain range, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to see, the brick floor and the elegant lanterns unmistakably support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
If you look up, you can see the park benches, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally bookshelves are arranged along the facade and in the center a huge dark room opens up that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
What we've done is we've turned the classical spatial configuration upside down and pulled the reading zone from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well developed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education centre and the maintenance room.
Special mention is given to black shelves that serve as wall coverings, parapets and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in Spijkenisse.
And so it is that one day, on a farm in Frisia, we come across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of a few millimeters thick has been used as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It's a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and then gets thrown away.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to four centimeters thick plates.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (APP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous, and resistant material that smells like a mixture of a new car and a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of nearly 500 meters around the mountain, we are rewarded: From the café you not only get a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere at par with the atmospheric humidity that is suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"While it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary ecological project", notes Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Even though the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun shines only for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located in a transverse direction to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about the automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the sceptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there, too.
Also, the professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library, calling the "Boekenberg" the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the opening ceremony that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This is intended to fill in the gaps in a library that has not yet been fully archived and currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows your book is part of the library.
Even if it's only there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved great success in that discipline which in the specialist slang is known as "creating an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point for shaping your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained from voting on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather acute diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories the status of a United Nations observer state.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
- Why? - I don't know.
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship that binds the country to Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I think it also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to prove its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is now refocusing its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to decide what their role will be, but they have already begun the path to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What exactly does a 'normal' foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, that is, exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests differ to some extent from those of other great powers and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give it that much importance since this isn't a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in the German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position is very much understood.
I therefore do not believe that there has been such a drastic breakdown as in Libya.
Perhaps Germany has thus earned some respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the United States has clearly shown itself in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
There have always been these disparities because of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I think the real disparity of views is not really the scale that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would be a little easier for the Germans, of course, if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but this is not the case.
They are therefore not able to be part of a higher entity, but must push things from their own standpoint.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
This is of course not easy for Germany, whether it is simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a hot topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as an important international actor?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to it, it is always uncomfortable and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany takes a leading role, certain anti-German sentiments are aroused.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and it is that no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The influence of the United States on European policy is declining, but the EU is not currently filling that gap.
The Germans will have no choice but to take a more leading role.
Even if they don't like it, if it makes them unpleasant or makes them an even more unpopular people, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is Armani Polo?
This name hides a name officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it is protected as long as the true eponymous does not bring a claim.
And even then it's not clear they're going to be right.
"Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China", notes Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Impersonators simply add a couple of letters to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as happened to the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a file cabinet where he keeps seats at the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010 a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name also used by the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large warehouses of various plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature.On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It's about women who have "fished" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities don't feel guilty
"It is harmful to business, we must fight it", Pattloch demands.
"The brand is flooded, the monopoly position is gone and the damage to the image is enormous".
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors affected are millions, especially for flagship luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year, China is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, the cancellation of doubtful registration marks in the trade mark register is complicated and also a lot of money.
The processes can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases where the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name under the lawsuit had already become a 'market reality'.
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money because the process has damaged the plaintiff's brand in China", Pattloch notes.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
