Bradley Manning did not report mistreatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse during his time in prison.
The trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dropped on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, charged with the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to denounce the mistreatment he now alleges he suffered while under military custody.
During the interrogation that prosecutors conducted on Manning in a preview of the trial in Ft. Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits by unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defense's request that the case be dismissed as his imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already meant sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in custody.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum security from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the cellists as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms show no reports of ill-treatment, although officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those issues and had indicated to him that they would be addressed, but that they had not recorded those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after having talked about the problems) but that doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems", Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the 'injury prevention' regime under which he was.
The military said it had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below that of possible suicide surveillance, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so that I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to just Camp Arafjon, that cage", Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage".
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, some slippers, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move around all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said if the lockers couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 regarding the treatment Manning received.
Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's statement that, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of cell clerks and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he inferred from the order given to him by the jailer that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used his underwear or his ankles to self-harm but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed their underwear, their ankles and their glasses from their cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she experienced during her time in prison and drastically reduce her sentence in case she was convicted at the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to make Manning guilty of misdemeanor charges and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of enforcement for all detainees who are in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawful publication of information on the Internet, leaking of national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If he's found guilty on all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
