The generic tobacco packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and body parts with diseases are lit on green-lit, off-the-shelf boxes, which are the same for all tobacco brands
Australia's world-first tobacco and generic packaging law comes into force and replaces brand logos and colors with an olive green blackout wrapper, scary images of sick body parts and depictions of children and babies who are sick because they are children of smoking parents.
Apart from the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, which are mandatory from Saturday, are the brand names, all of them printed in a small font.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regimen in the world.
The Australian federal government claims that the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
He relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
"You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand", said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has put enormous pressure on the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black market in tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will have serious unintended consequences", said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Others say their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for splinters and silicone lids to cover the nasty images of the boxes had skyrocketed almost from scratch two months ago when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a lawsuit in Australia's Supreme Court.
Mrs. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and was expecting more stocks.
"It's a good deal for us".
According to experts, the potential obstacle is the popularity of social media among the demographic sector targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and requiring most sellers not to show cigarettes, tobacco marketing has shifted to online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Internet for local businesses and websites, but it cannot restrict it to foreign sites.
"If you're marketing tobacco and you only have this little window to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be", said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in brand reviews from "loyal citizens" posted on social media websites like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if it's just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
British American Tobacco of Australia said the industry is more focused on what the new regulations involve than on marketing.
Industry has even come to pay for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to refuse the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, even though neither of these countries has a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek claimed that the government had held talks with other countries that are considering applying similar laws on tobacco packaging.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the mandatory inclusion of images in the box.
