"The government should have banned tobacco altogether and then, that's it, okay, it's over and we close the store", he says as he raises his hands up.
In a world that's constantly connected, it's not so bad to get bored a little bit.
During this year's Thanksgiving party, unexpectedly, I had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have means to be entertained, like books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting duty-free shops.
But there are more and more academics and child development experts who praise the goodness of boredom.
They say that it is okay for us and our children to get bored from time to time.
Boredom forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are now connected to this or that screen, we don't experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom with goodwill?
- I know.
And no, you can't.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that now that we have more leisure time, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the 2011 book "Boredom: A Lively History" published by Yale University Press, says, this is not true.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti on boredom dating from the 1st century AD.
We also need to consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways", says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining published research and raising the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wishing, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you".
He says the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn't do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly".
