Unasur summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without making public the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending presidents.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but sources from the Chancellery and the Presidency pointed out that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later they said that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they noted that the content had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information at the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the silent video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information circulated among reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is Humala's pronouncement, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite press pressing demands, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not even circulated.
The official website of ASPA confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited information collection to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with Chile and Peru's joint commitment to accept a ruling by the Hague Court settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both sides, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will accept and execute the sentence that defines the differences we are bringing to this international court today", Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will remain a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts", added Piñera, and saluted Humala with a handshake, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the judgments of that international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was held with the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the appointment.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and action lines were set for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residency".
He said that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost internet access in all corners of South America, and to jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand the productive matrix and to see a better future for our peoples", added Humala.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas...by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the cross-axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve its reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations", of which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbors was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaragua counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat the maritime dispute respectfully after a CIJ ruling, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these roads, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell you that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers met previously to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
